Vladimir Putin and the Risk of a Third World War
San Francisco — On February 24, Russia's invasion of Ukraine marked the beginning of a potential third world war that could destroy our civilization.
Before the invasion, Russian President Vladimir Putin and Chinese President Xi Jinping held a prolonged meeting on February 4th — a day marking the start of the Chinese Lunar New Year celebrations and the Beijing Winter Olympic Games.
After the meeting, the two leaders released a meticulously drafted 5,000-word document announcing the establishment of a close partnership between the two countries.
This document is more powerful than any treaty and certainly requires careful negotiations in advance.
I am shocked that Xi seems to have fully entrusted Putin with invading and launching the war in Ukraine.
He believed that his confirmation as China's lifelong ruler in the latter half of this year was merely a formality, and he was undoubtedly confident about it.
After consolidating all power in his own hands, Xi carefully planned a strategy to elevate himself to the level of Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping.
After securing Xi's support, Putin set out to realize his lifelong dream in an unbelievable brutal manner.
Putin, nearly 70 years old, feels that if he wants to leave a significant mark in Russian history, it has to be now, or it will never happen.
But his view of Russia's role in the world is distorted.
It seems he believes that the Russian people need a tsar they can blindly follow.
This system is the exact opposite of a democratic society, and this vision distorts the "soul" of the Russian people, whose emotions have been twisted into sentimental excess.
As a child, I had a lot of contact with Russian soldiers who occupied Hungary in 1945.
I know that if you ask them, they will share their last piece of bread with you.
Later, in the early 1980s, I embarked on what I called my political philanthropy.
At first, I established a foundation in my homeland, Hungary, and later I actively participated in activities that contributed to the dissolution of the Soviet Empire.
The disintegration had already begun when Mikhail Gorbachev came to power in 1985.
I also established a foundation in Russia, and later in each of the newly independent republics.
I established a foundation in Ukraine even before it became an independent country.
I also visited China in 1984 and became the first foreigner allowed to establish a foundation there (I closed this foundation in 1989, and shortly thereafter the massacre at Tiananmen Square occurred).
I personally don't know Putin, but I have been closely watching his rise to power and fully understand his ruthless personality.
He reduced Grozny, the capital of Chechnya, to rubble, and now he threatens to do the same to Kyiv, the capital of Ukraine.
Putin was once a shrewd KGB officer, but he seems to have changed recently.
He seemed to have lost touch with reality because he had formed a fixed notion.
Undoubtedly, he misjudged the situation in Ukraine.
He had thought that Russian-speaking Ukrainians would open their arms to welcome Russian soldiers, but it turned out that they were no different from the Ukrainian-speaking population.
Faced with what seemed like an overwhelming possibility, the Ukrainian people have shown incredible bravery in their resistance.
In July 2021, Putin published a long article stating that Russians and Ukrainians are actually one nation, and that Ukrainians have been misled by neo-Nazi agitators.
Because Kyiv is the original site of the Russian Orthodox Church, his first argument is not without historical basis.
But in the content of Part 2, it is Putin who is misled.
He should have known the facts more clearly.
Many Ukrainians bravely fought in the Euromaidan protests that erupted in 2014.
The 2014 incident made him very angry.
However, Russian forces performed poorly when ordered to attack their Ukrainian counterparts.
The deep-rooted corruption in the Ministry of Defense when awarding contracts also played a significant role in this poor performance.
But instead of blaming himself, Putin seemed to have gone mad.
He has already decided to punish Ukraine for opposing him, and his actions seem to be unconstrained.
He threw the entire Russian army into battle and ignored all rules of engagement, particularly indiscriminately bombing civilian populations.
Many hospitals were attacked, and the power grid supplying the Chernobyl nuclear power plant (currently occupied by Russian forces) was also damaged.
In the besieged Mariupol, as many as 400,000 people have had no water or food for nearly a week.
Russia is likely to lose this war.
Both the United States and the European Union are sending defensive weapons to Ukraine, while also attempting to purchase Russian-made MIG fighter jets that Ukrainian pilots know how to operate.
These could change the entire situation.
No matter the outcome, Putin has created a miracle in strengthening Europe's determination and solidarity.
At the same time, Xi apparently realized that Putin had been unfaithful.
On March 8, after Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi asserted that Sino-Russian friendship remains "as solid as a rock," President Xi called French President Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz, expressing his support for their peacekeeping efforts.
To prevent a humanitarian crisis, he hopes for the maximum restraint during the war.
It is still fundamentally uncertain whether Putin will accommodate Xi's wishes.
We can only hope that Putin and Xi will be removed from power before they destroy our civilization.
